No accounting for taste and all, but I simply hated it. The main plot takes about 300 pages to get started, and isn't very compelling. What could be called a secondary plot barely receives any real progress. The worldbuilding is rickety, so where there's a relatively interesting idea in the "remaking" which is essentially Fantasy cybernetics, no-one seems to use it for practical purposes. Which is weird, considering the author is a communist who isn't shy about bringing his politics into the book. So you'd figure there'd be the usual Cyberpunk thing with workers being forced to give up their humanity for the bottom line, but if it was there in the book, I don't recall it. There's also a Deus Ex Machina moment which I really hated. The antagonists are comically evil and involve themselves into a lot of dead ends trying to deal with the main plot that are just completely superfluous except for showing how "weird" the setting is. There are also pointless asides for the author's love for D&D, and his dislike of weapons of mass destruction. These take several pages, mind you.

It could have been readable with some vigorous editing. The author's style is often a point of contention, as it's pretty pretentious, but nothing really sticks in my memory of it. I think he just likes using strange analogies and using words like "lugubrious". Nothing that would impress anyone with a decent command of the English language.
